'''Edward M. Daily''' (September 7, 1862 – October 21, 1891), was a [[Major League Baseball]] player. He played seven seasons in the majors, from {{Baseball year|1885}} until {{Baseball year|1891}}, for the [[Philadelphia Phillies]], [[Washington Nationals (1886–89)|Washington Nationals]], [[Columbus Solons]], [[Brooklyn Gladiators]], [[New York Giants (NL)|New York Giants]], [[Louisville Colonels]], and [[Washington Statesmen (1891)|Washington Statesmen]]
Daily began his Major League career as a [[pitcher]] for the [[Philadelphia Quakers (NL)|Philadelphia Quakers]] in {{Baseball year|1885}}. He won 26 games, fifth in the [[National League]]. In {{Baseball year|1886}}, he went 16–9, but was already starting to play more often as an [[outfielder]], appearing in 56 games in the outfield and batting .227. From {{Baseball year|1887}} until {{Baseball year|1889}}, he was almost exclusively an outfielder, but in {{Baseball year|1890}} he pitched in 41 games for three teams, winning 18 games. He played part of one more season in the majors, but died shortly after the end of the season.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/d/dailyed01.shtml|title=Ed Daily Stats - Baseball-Reference.com|website=Baseball-Reference.com|accessdate=2 September 2017}}</ref>
