'''Konrad [[Freiherr]] von Wangenheim''' (20 August 1909 – 28 January 1953) was a German army [[Cavalry]] officer, a horse rider who competed at the [[1936 Summer Olympics]] in [[Berlin]], securing a gold medal for the German [[Equestrianism|equestrian]] team whilst suffering from a broken [[Clavicle|collarbone]].

In 1936 he and his horse ''Kurfürst'' won the gold medal as part of the German [[eventing]] team in the team eventing competition after finishing 24th in the [[Equestrian at the 1936 Summer Olympics|individual eventing competition]].

Wangenheim became a [[Captain (OF-2)|Captain]] (''[[Rittmeister]]'') with Cavalry Regiment No. 8 (''Reiter-Regiment 8'', later renamed ''Kavallerie-Regiment 8'') [[garrison]]ed at [[Brzeg|Breig]] in [[Silesia]]. In July 1944, while serving as a [[German Army (Wehrmacht)|German Army]] officer on the [[Eastern Front (World War II)|Eastern Front]] during the [[Second World War]], he was captured by the [[Red Army]]. After being held as a prisoner of war for several years, while awaiting repatriation to Germany from the [[Soviet Union]], in 1953 he was found hanged in [[Volgograd|Stalingrad]], [[Russian Soviet Federative Socialist Republic|Russia]]. He may have committed suicide.<ref>{{cite journal|date=Nov–Dec 2006|title=Chris von Wangenheim|journal=American Photo|volume=17|issue=6|page=61|issn=1046-8986|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=R4UzETDM5ccC&pg=PA89&dq=chris+von+wangenheim&hl=en&sa=X&ei=vu6WUP3SHoW22gWej4GgAw&ved=0CDIQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=chris%20von%20wangenheim&f=false}}</ref>

He was the father of the professional fashion photographer [[Chris von Wangenheim]].

